{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QE7uak8xgrcpBPXaqQBhcG","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tstepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4]\n3\tstatus: complete\n4\tinputDocuments:\n5\t  - prd.md (multi-framework orchestration PRD, 2026-04-03)\n6\t  - architecture-multi-framework.md (multi-framework architecture, 2026-04-03)\n7\t---\n8\t\n9\t# codeharness - Epic Breakdown (Multi-Framework Orchestration)\n10\t\n11\t## Overview\n12\t\n13\tThis document provides the complete epic and story breakdown for codeharness multi-framework orchestration, decomposing the requirements from the PRD and Architecture into implementable stories.\n14\t\n15\t## Requirements Inventory\n16\t\n17\t### Functional Requirements\n18\t\n19\t- FR1: System can register and resolve agent drivers by name (claude-code, codex, opencode)\n20\t- FR2: System can detect whether a driver's CLI binary is installed and accessible on the system PATH\n21\t- FR3: System can verify a driver's authentication status before task dispatch\n22\t- FR4: System can report missing or unauthenticated drivers with install/auth instructions at workflow start\n23\t- FR5: System can spawn an agent process via the appropriate driver's CLI invocation\n24\t- FR6: System can terminate a running driver process on task timeout, cancellation, or circuit breaker\n25\t- FR7: Each driver can parse its framework's CLI output into the common StreamEvent protocol\n26\t- FR8: System can capture cost information from driver output and normalize to cost_usd\n27\t- FR9: System can classify driver errors into standard categories (RATE_LIMIT, NETWORK, AUTH, TIMEOUT, UNKNOWN)\n28\t- FR10: System can detect and report when a driver's output format is unparseable\n29\t- FR11: User can specify a driver field per task in workflow YAML (optional, defaults to claude-code)\n30\t- FR12: User can specify a model field per task in workflow YAML (optional, overrides agent default)\n31\t- FR13: System can resolve the effective model for a task via the resolution chain: task model → agent model → driver default\n32\t- FR14: System can validate workflow YAML referential integrity — all referenced drivers exist, all referenced agents exist\n33\t- FR15: System can load existing workflows without driver/model fields with full backward compatibility\n34\t- FR16: System can execute a workflow where consecutive tasks use different drivers\n35\t- FR17: System can serialize a task's output contract to a structured JSON file after task completion\n36\t- FR18: System can load a previous task's output contract and inject it as context into the next task's prompt\n37\t- FR19: System can pass acceptance criteria, changed file lists, and test results across framework boundaries via output contracts\n38\t- FR20: System can execute verification tasks on a different framework than implementation tasks within the same story\n39\t- FR21: User can configure gstack skills to load within claude-code driver sessions via workflow or agent config\n40\t- FR22: User can configure omo agents to load within opencode driver sessions via workflow or agent config\n41\t- FR23: System can pass plugin-specific configuration to the driver's CLI invocation\n42\t- FR24: System can render a schematic workflow graph in the Ink TUI showing all tasks as nodes with directional flow\n43\t- FR25: System can highlight the currently executing task node in the workflow graph\n44\t- FR26: System can display the driver name (framework label) under each task node in the workflow graph\n45\t- FR27: System can display accumulated cost and elapsed time per completed task node\n46\t- FR28: System can render loop blocks in the workflow graph with visual grouping and iteration counter\n47\t- FR29: System can update the workflow graph position within 500ms of a task transition\n48\t- FR30: System can show task completion status (checkmark, spinner, pending) per node in the workflow graph\n49\t- FR31: System can display stream events from any driver in the activity section\n50\t- FR32: System can display the active driver name alongside tool activity\n51\t- FR33: System can display per-story cost breakdown by driver in the story breakdown section\n52\t- FR34: System can accumulate cost per driver across a workflow run\n53\t- FR35: System can display total cost per driver in the TUI\n54\t- FR36: System can suggest a cheaper driver for tasks that don't require the capabilities of the configured driver\n55\t- FR37: System can document each driver's capabilities in a queryable format\n56\t- FR38: System can warn at workflow start if a task's requirements conflict with the driver's capabilities\n57\t\n58\t### Non-Functional Requirements\n59\t\n60\t- NFR1: Driver spawn (CLI cold start to first output) must complete within 3 seconds\n61\t- NFR2: TUI workflow graph position update must render within 500ms of task transition\n62\t- NFR3: Stream event parsing must keep up with driver output rate — no dropped events\n63\t- NFR4: Output contract serialization/deserialization must complete within 1 second for contracts up to 1MB\n64\t- NFR5: TUI render loop must maintain 15 FPS maximum without CPU spikes\n65\t- NFR6: Driver health check (all drivers in workflow) must complete within 5 seconds at workflow start\n66\t- NFR7: Codex driver must work with Codex CLI versions pinned in package.json\n67\t- NFR8: OpenCode driver must work with OpenCode CLI versions pinned in package.json\n68\t- NFR9: Claude Code driver must maintain compatibility with Agent SDK pinned version\n69\t- NFR10: Output contract JSON format must be stable across driver versions\n70\t- NFR11: Workflow YAML schema changes must be backward compatible\n71\t- NFR12: Plugin ecosystem integration must not require modifications to the plugins themselves\n72\t- NFR13: If a driver process crashes mid-task, the engine must detect it within 5 seconds\n73\t- NFR14: If a driver's CLI output format is unparseable, the engine must surface the raw output for debugging\n74\t- NFR15: Output contract files must survive engine crashes — written atomically\n75\t- NFR16: Driver timeout must be configurable per task (default: 30 minutes)\n76\t- NFR17: TUI must remain responsive during driver failures\n77\t- NFR18: Workflow engine must be idempotent for re-runs — resume from last completed task\n78\t\n79\t### Additional Requirements (from Architecture)\n80\t\n81\t- Existing AgentDriver interface must be refactored to use AsyncIterable<StreamEvent> instead of spawn()/AgentProcess\n82\t- Claude Code driver refactored from existing agent-dispatch.ts into driver class\n83\t- Driver factory pattern with explicit registration (no auto-discovery)\n84\t- Output contracts stored in .codeharness/contracts/{taskName}-{storyId}.json with atomic writes\n85\t- Model resolution chain: task → agent → driver default (3-level cascade)\n86\t- WorkflowGraph Ink component inserted between Header and StoryBreakdown\n87\t- Plugin pass-through via plugins array in workflow YAML task definition\n88\t- All drivers must follow identical class structure per architecture implementation patterns\n89\t- Fixture-based testing required for all drivers (real CLI output samples)\n90\t\n91\t### FR Coverage Map\n92\t\n93\t| FR | Epic | Description |\n94\t|----|------|-------------|\n95\t| FR1 | Epic 1 | Register and resolve drivers by name |\n96\t| FR2 | Epic 3 | Detect CLI binary on PATH |\n97\t| FR3 | Epic 3 | Verify driver auth status |\n98\t| FR4 | Epic 3 | Report missing drivers with install instructions |\n99\t| FR5 | Epic 1, 3 | Spawn agent process via driver CLI |\n100\t| FR6 | Epic 1 | Terminate driver on timeout/cancellation |\n101\t| FR7 | Epic 1, 3 | Parse CLI output to StreamEvent |\n102\t| FR8 | Epic 1, 3 | Capture and normalize cost_usd |\n103\t| FR9 | Epic 1, 3 | Classify driver errors into standard categories |\n104\t| FR10 | Epic 1, 3 | Detect and report unparseable output |\n105\t| FR11 | Epic 2 | Per-task driver field in workflow YAML |\n106\t| FR12 | Epic 2 | Per-task model field in workflow YAML |\n107\t| FR13 | Epic 1, 2 | Model resolution chain |\n108\t| FR14 | Epic 2 | Workflow YAML referential integrity |\n109\t| FR15 | Epic 1, 2 | Backward compatibility for old workflows |\n110\t| FR16 | Epic 4 | Execute workflow with different drivers per task |\n111\t| FR17 | Epic 4 | Serialize output contract to JSON |\n112\t| FR18 | Epic 4 | Load and inject output contract into next task |\n113\t| FR19 | Epic 4 | Pass ACs, files, tests across framework boundaries |\n114\t| FR20 | Epic 4 | Verification on different framework than implementation |\n115\t| FR21 | Epic 6 | Configure gstack skills in claude-code sessions |\n116\t| FR22 | Epic 6 | Configure omo agents in opencode sessions |\n117\t| FR23 | Epic 6 | Pass plugin config to driver CLI invocation |\n118\t| FR24 | Epic 5 | Render workflow graph in TUI |\n119\t| FR25 | Epic 5 | Highlight current task node |\n120\t| FR26 | Epic 5 | Display driver name under each node |\n121\t| FR27 | Epic 5 | Display cost/time per completed node |\n122\t| FR28 | Epic 5 | Render loop blocks with iteration counter |\n123\t| FR29 | Epic 5 | Update position within 500ms |\n124\t| FR30 | Epic 5 | Show completion status per node |\n125\t| FR31 | Epic 5 | Display stream events from any driver |\n126\t| FR32 | Epic 5 | Display active driver name in activity |\n127\t| FR33 | Epic 5 | Per-story cost breakdown by driver |\n128\t| FR34 | Epic 6 | Accumulate cost per driver |\n129\t| FR35 | Epic 6 | Display total cost per driver in TUI |\n130\t| FR36 | Epic 6 | Suggest cheaper driver (routing hint) |\n131\t| FR37 | Epic 6 | Driver capabilities in queryable format |\n132\t| FR38 | Epic 6 | Warn on task/driver capability conflicts |\n133\t\n134\t## Epic List\n135\t\n136\t### Epic 1: Driver Interface & Claude Code Refactor\n137\tUsers can run workflows using the formalized driver abstraction, with the existing Claude Code Agent SDK refactored into a proper driver class. Everything works exactly as before, but through the new AgentDriver interface.\n138\t**FRs covered:** FR1, FR5, FR6, FR7, FR8, FR9, FR10, FR13, FR15\n139\t\n140\t### Epic 2: Workflow Schema & Model Resolution\n141\tUsers can configure driver and model per task in workflow YAML. The workflow engine resolves models via the 3-level cascade and validates referential integrity. Backward compatible.\n142\t**FRs covered:** FR11, FR12, FR13, FR14, FR15\n143\t\n144\t### Epic 3: Codex & OpenCode Drivers\n145\tUsers can dispatch tasks to Codex CLI and OpenCode CLI. Both drivers implement AgentDriver, parse CLI output to StreamEvent, and handle health checks.\n146\t**FRs covered:** FR2, FR3, FR4, FR5, FR7, FR8, FR9, FR10\n147\t\n148\t### Epic 4: Cross-Framework Execution & Output Contracts\n149\tUsers can run workflows where consecutive tasks use different frameworks, with output contracts passing context between them. Cross-framework verification works end-to-end.\n150\t**FRs covered:** FR16, FR17, FR18, FR19, FR20\n151\t\n152\t### Epic 5: TUI Workflow Visualization\n153\tUsers can see the workflow graph in the TUI with current position, driver labels, cost/time per node, and loop counters. Activity display shows which driver is active.\n154\t**FRs covered:** FR24, FR25, FR26, FR27, FR28, FR29, FR30, FR31, FR32, FR33\n155\t\n156\t### Epic 6: Plugin Ecosystem & Cost Intelligence\n157\tUsers can configure gstack/omo plugins per task, see cost breakdowns per driver, and get routing hints for cheaper alternatives. Driver capability matrix warns about conflicts.\n158\t**FRs covered:** FR21, FR22, FR23, FR34, FR35, FR36, FR37, FR38\n159\t\n160\t## Epic 1: Driver Interface & Claude Code Refactor\n161\t\n162\tUsers can run workflows using the formalized driver abstraction, with the existing Claude Code Agent SDK refactored into a proper driver class.\n163\t\n164\t### Story 1.1: AgentDriver Interface & Types\n165\t\n166\tAs a developer,\n167\tI want a formalized AgentDriver interface with DriverHealth, DispatchOpts, and StreamEvent types,\n168\tSo that all drivers implement a consistent contract.\n169\t\n170\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n171\t\n172\t**Given** the existing `src/lib/agents/types.ts`\n173\t**When** the interface is refactored\n174\t**Then** `AgentDriver` has `name`, `defaultModel`, `capabilities`, `healthCheck()`, `dispatch()`, `getLastCost()` methods\n175\t**And** `DispatchOpts` includes `prompt`, `model`, `cwd`, `sourceAccess`, `plugins`, `timeout`, `outputContract`\n176\t**And** `DriverHealth` includes `available`, `authenticated`, `version`, `error`\n177\t**And** `dispatch()` returns `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>`\n178\t**And** all existing StreamEvent types are preserved\n179\t\n180\t### Story 1.2: Driver Factory & Registry\n181\t\n182\tAs a developer,\n183\tI want a driver factory that registers and resolves drivers by name,\n184\tSo that the workflow engine can get any driver without knowing its implementation.\n185\t\n186\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n187\t\n188\t**Given** a new `src/lib/agents/drivers/factory.ts`\n189\t**When** `getDriver('claude-code')` is called\n190\t**Then** it returns the registered ClaudeCodeDriver instance\n191\t**And** `getDriver('unknown')` throws a descriptive error\n192\t**And** `listDrivers()` returns all registered driver names\n193\t**And** drivers are registered explicitly (no auto-discovery)\n194\t\n195\t### Story 1.3: Claude Code Driver Extraction\n196\t\n197\tAs a developer,\n198\tI want the existing Agent SDK dispatch logic extracted into a ClaudeCodeDriver class,\n199\tSo that Claude Code works through the same driver interface as future drivers.\n200\t\n201\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n202\t\n203\t**Given** the existing `agent-dispatch.ts` dispatch logic\n204\t**When** refactored into `src/lib/agents/drivers/claude-code.ts`\n205\t**Then** `ClaudeCodeDriver` implements `AgentDriver` interface\n206\t**And** `dispatch()` calls Agent SDK `query()` and yields `StreamEvent` objects\n207\t**And** `healthCheck()` returns `{ available: true, authenticated: true }`\n208\t**And** `getLastCost()` returns cost from the last Agent SDK dispatch\n209\t**And** error classification maps Agent SDK errors to RATE_LIMIT, NETWORK, AUTH, TIMEOUT, UNKNOWN\n210\t**And** existing workflow execution produces identical results through the driver\n211\t\n212\t### Story 1.4: Model Resolution Module\n213\t\n214\tAs a developer,\n215\tI want a model resolver that cascades task → agent → driver defaults,\n216\tSo that the effective model for any task dispatch is deterministic.\n217\t\n218\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n219\t\n220\t**Given** a new `src/lib/agents/model-resolver.ts`\n221\t**When** `resolveModel(task, agent, driver)` is called\n222\t**Then** task-level model takes highest priority\n223\t**And** agent-level model is used if task has no model\n224\t**And** driver default model is used if neither task nor agent specify one\n225\t**And** the resolved model is returned as a string\n226\t**And** backward compatible with existing workflows that have no model field\n227\t\n228\t### Story 1.5: Workflow Engine Driver Integration\n229\t\n230\tAs a developer,\n231\tI want the workflow engine to dispatch tasks through the driver factory,\n232\tSo that switching drivers is a configuration change, not a code change.\n233\t\n234\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n235\t\n236\t**Given** the existing `workflow-engine.ts`\n237\t**When** executing a workflow task\n238\t**Then** the engine resolves the driver from the factory (defaulting to `claude-code`)\n239\t**And** the engine calls `driver.dispatch(opts)` instead of `dispatchAgent()` directly\n240\t**And** the engine consumes `AsyncIterable<StreamEvent>` from the driver\n241\t**And** existing workflows without `driver` field work identically\n242\t**And** driver process termination works on timeout/cancellation\n243\t\n244\t## Epic 2: Workflow Schema & Model Resolution\n245\t\n246\tUsers can configure driver and model per task in workflow YAML with backward compatibility.\n247\t\n248\t### Story 2.1: Workflow Schema Extension\n249\t\n250\tAs a user,\n251\tI want to specify `driver` and `model` per task in my workflow YAML,\n252\tSo that I can control which framework and model each task uses.\n253\t\n254\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n255\t\n256\t**Given** `src/schemas/workflow.schema.json`\n257\t**When** updated with `driver`, `model`, and `plugins` fields on task definition\n258\t**Then** `driver` is optional with default `claude-code`\n259\t**And** `model` is optional with no default (falls through to resolution chain)\n260\t**And** `plugins` is optional array of strings\n261\t**And** existing workflows without these fields validate successfully\n262\t**And** `workflow-parser.ts` parses the new fields from YAML\n263\t\n264\t### Story 2.2: Workflow Referential Integrity Validation\n265\t\n266\tAs a user,\n267\tI want the workflow parser to validate that all referenced drivers and agents exist,\n268\tSo that I get clear errors before execution if my config is wrong.\n269\t\n270\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n271\t\n272\t**Given** a workflow YAML with `driver: codex` on a task\n273\t**When** the workflow is parsed and validated\n274\t**Then** the parser checks that `codex` is a registered driver name\n275\t**And** the parser checks that all referenced agent names exist in agent templates\n276\t**And** validation errors include the specific field, task name, and suggested fix\n277\t**And** validation runs at parse time before any task dispatch\n278\t\n279\t## Epic 3: Codex & OpenCode Drivers\n280\t\n281\tUsers can dispatch tasks to Codex CLI and OpenCode CLI with full health checking.\n282\t\n283\t### Story 3.1: Codex Driver Implementation\n284\t\n285\tAs a user,\n286\tI want to run tasks on OpenAI Codex by setting `driver: codex`,\n287\tSo that I can use Codex models for implementation or verification.\n288\t\n289\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n290\t\n291\t**Given** a new `src/lib/agents/drivers/codex.ts`\n292\t**When** `dispatch()` is called\n293\t**Then** the driver spawns `codex` CLI via `child_process.spawn`\n294\t**And** stdout is parsed line-by-line into `StreamEvent` objects\n295\t**And** unparseable lines are logged at debug level and skipped\n296\t**And** a `result` event is always yielded at the end (even on error)\n297\t**And** cost is captured from CLI output or set to `null`\n298\t**And** `healthCheck()` checks `which codex`, version, and auth status\n299\t**And** missing binary returns `{ available: false, error: \"codex CLI not found. Install: npm install -g @openai/codex\" }`\n300\t**And** fixture-based tests exist in `test/fixtures/drivers/codex/`\n301\t\n302\t### Story 3.2: OpenCode Driver Implementation\n303\t\n304\tAs a user,\n305\tI want to run tasks on OpenCode by setting `driver: opencode`,\n306\tSo that I can use OpenCode's multi-model support for any task.\n307\t\n308\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n309\t\n310\t**Given** a new `src/lib/agents/drivers/opencode.ts`\n311\t**When** `dispatch()` is called\n312\t**Then** the driver spawns `opencode` CLI via `child_process.spawn`\n313\t**And** stdout is parsed line-by-line into `StreamEvent` objects\n314\t**And** unparseable lines are logged at debug level and skipped\n315\t**And** a `result` event is always yielded at the end (even on error)\n316\t**And** cost is captured from CLI output or set to `null`\n317\t**And** `healthCheck()` checks `which opencode`, version, and auth status\n318\t**And** missing binary returns `{ available: false, error: \"opencode not found. Install: https://opencode.ai\" }`\n319\t**And** fixture-based tests exist in `test/fixtures/drivers/opencode/`\n320\t\n321\t### Story 3.3: Driver Health Check at Workflow Start\n322\t\n323\tAs a user,\n324\tI want all referenced drivers health-checked before any task executes,\n325\tSo that I get immediate feedback if a CLI is missing or unauthenticated.\n326\t\n327\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n328\t\n329\t**Given** a workflow referencing drivers `claude-code` and `codex`\n330\t**When** `codeharness run` starts\n331\t**Then** the engine calls `healthCheck()` on every unique driver in the workflow\n332\t**And** all health checks complete within 5 seconds total (NFR6)\n333\t**And** if any driver is unavailable, the run aborts with a clear error listing all failing drivers\n334\t**And** if all drivers are healthy, the run proceeds normally\n335\t\n336\t## Epic 4: Cross-Framework Execution & Output Contracts\n337\t\n338\tUsers can run workflows where consecutive tasks use different frameworks with data passing between them.\n339\t\n340\t### Story 4.1: Output Contract Schema & Serialization\n341\t\n342\tAs a developer,\n343\tI want output contracts serialized as JSON files with atomic writes,\n344\tSo that task results survive crashes and can be read by the next task.\n345\t\n346\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n347\t\n348\t**Given** a new `src/lib/agents/output-contract.ts` and `src/schemas/output-contract.schema.json`\n349\t**When** a task completes\n350\t**Then** the engine writes a contract to `.codeharness/contracts/{taskName}-{storyId}.json`\n351\t**And** the write is atomic (write to `.tmp`, then rename)\n352\t**And** the contract includes version, taskName, storyId, driver, model, timestamp, cost_usd, duration_ms, changedFiles, testResults, output, acceptanceCriteria\n353\t**And** fields that aren't available are set to `null`\n354\t**And** serialization/deserialization completes within 1 second for contracts up to 1MB (NFR4)\n355\t\n356\t### Story 4.2: Output Contract Prompt Injection\n357\t\n358\tAs a developer,\n359\tI want the previous task's output contract injected into the next task's prompt,\n360\tSo that cross-framework tasks have context from the previous step.\n361\t\n362\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n363\t\n364\t**Given** a completed task with a written output contract\n365\t**When** the next task in the workflow starts\n366\t**Then** the engine reads the previous contract and formats it as structured prompt context\n367\t**And** the prompt includes changed files, test results, output summary, AC statuses\n368\t**And** the injection is framework-agnostic\n369\t**And** if no previous contract exists (first task), no injection occurs\n370\t\n371\t### Story 4.3: Cross-Framework Workflow Execution\n372\t\n373\tAs a user,\n374\tI want to run a workflow where implement uses claude-code and verify uses codex,\n375\tSo that verification is structurally independent from implementation.\n376\t\n377\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n378\t\n379\t**Given** a workflow with `implement: { driver: claude-code }` and `verify: { driver: codex }`\n380\t**When** `codeharness run` executes\n381\t**Then** the implement task runs via Claude Code driver\n382\t**And** on completion, an output contract is written\n383\t**And** the verify task starts via Codex driver with the output contract injected\n384\t**And** loop blocks correctly alternate between drivers\n385\t**And** the workflow engine resumes from the last completed task on re-run (NFR18)\n386\t\n387\t## Epic 5: TUI Workflow Visualization\n388\t\n389\tUsers can see the workflow graph in the TUI with current position, driver labels, cost/time, and loop counters.\n390\t\n391\t### Story 5.1: WorkflowGraph Component\n392\t\n393\tAs a user,\n394\tI want to see a schematic workflow graph in the TUI,\n395\tSo that I can see all tasks, their order, and loop blocks at a glance.\n396\t\n397\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n398\t\n399\t**Given** a new `src/lib/ink-workflow.tsx`\n400\t**When** a workflow is running\n401\t**Then** the TUI renders a workflow graph between Header and StoryBreakdown\n402\t**And** each task is shown as a node with its name\n403\t**And** nodes are connected with `→` arrows\n404\t**And** loop blocks are rendered as `loop(N)[ task1 → task2 ]` with iteration count\n405\t**And** the component receives `flow`, `currentTask`, and `taskStates` as props\n406\t\n407\t### Story 5.2: Task Status & Driver Labels\n408\t\n409\tAs a user,\n410\tI want each workflow node to show its status, driver, and cost,\n411\tSo that I can see what's running, on which framework, and what it costs.\n412\t\n413\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n414\t\n415\t**Given** the WorkflowGraph component\n416\t**When** a task is pending → dim text\n417\t**And** when active → cyan + spinner\n418\t**And** when done → green ✓\n419\t**And** when failed → red ✗\n420\t**And** the driver name is displayed dimmed below each node\n421\t**And** cost and elapsed time are displayed below driver name for completed nodes\n422\t**And** the graph updates within 500ms of task transition (NFR2)\n423\t\n424\t### Story 5.3: Activity Display Driver Integration\n425\t\n426\tAs a user,\n427\tI want to see which driver is active in the tool activity section,\n428\tSo that I know which framework is executing the current tool call.\n429\t\n430\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n431\t\n432\t**Given** the existing activity display components\n433\t**When** stream events arrive from any driver\n434\t**Then** the active driver name is shown alongside tool activity\n435\t**And** per-story cost breakdown shows cost by driver\n436\t**And** the TUI remains responsive during driver failures (NFR17)\n437\t\n438\t## Epic 6: Plugin Ecosystem & Cost Intelligence\n439\t\n440\tUsers can configure gstack/omo plugins, track costs per driver, and get capability warnings.\n441\t\n442\t### Story 6.1: Plugin Pass-Through Configuration\n443\t\n444\tAs a user,\n445\tI want to specify plugins per task in workflow YAML,\n446\tSo that gstack skills load in Claude Code sessions and omo agents load in OpenCode sessions.\n447\t\n448\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n449\t\n450\t**Given** a workflow task with `plugins: ['gstack']` on a claude-code driver\n451\t**When** the driver dispatches the task\n452\t**Then** the driver translates the plugin config to framework-specific CLI flags\n453\t**And** codex driver warns and ignores unsupported plugins\n454\t**And** plugin configuration does not require modifying the plugins themselves (NFR12)\n455\t\n456\t### Story 6.2: Cost Tracking Per Driver\n457\t\n458\tAs a user,\n459\tI want to see accumulated cost per driver across a workflow run,\n460\tSo that I can compare framework costs and optimize.\n461\t\n462\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n463\t\n464\t**Given** a multi-driver workflow run\n465\t**When** tasks complete on different drivers\n466\t**Then** the engine accumulates cost per driver\n467\t**And** total cost per driver is displayed in the TUI\n468\t**And** drivers that don't report cost show `null` (not $0)\n469\t\n470\t### Story 6.3: Driver Capability Matrix & Routing Hints\n471\t\n472\tAs a user,\n473\tI want the system to warn me about capability conflicts and suggest cheaper alternatives,\n474\tSo that I avoid misconfigurations and optimize costs.\n475\t\n476\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n477\t\n478\t**Given** driver capabilities defined in `factory.ts`\n479\t**When** a workflow starts\n480\t**Then** the engine warns if a task's requirements conflict with the driver's capabilities\n481\t**And** `codeharness drivers` CLI command outputs capabilities as structured JSON\n482\t**And** when a task's driver costs >2x the cheapest capable alternative, an advisory message is displayed\n483\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01DJn3zvMdrKyrbtqTXgfYoQ","session_id":"61d40628-eabe-45b5-b544-2f5989944a22","uuid":"82e7ca91-7f2d-4d90-9f00-8e4c6da597ef","timestamp":"2026-04-03T06:38:43.935Z"}
{"type":"system","subtype":"task_progress","task_id":"a6a5607374c089082","tool_use_id":"toolu_01DJn3zvMdrKyrbtqTXgfYoQ","description":"Reading _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-multi-framework.md","usage":{"total_tokens":20076,"tool_uses":10,"duration_ms":16537},"last_tool_name":"Read","uuid":"5fd8c32b-5c01-4624-b1a2-7cf4f693fc05","session_id":"61d40628-eabe-45b5-b544-2f5989944a22"}
